##Ensure that your directory structure looks like this:
.
└── Dockerfile

##Building the Docker Image
cd /opt
sudo docker image build -t my-prometheus-image:v2.46.0 -f docker/image/prometheus/2.46.0/amazon-linux-2.dockerfile docker/image/prometheus/2.46.0/context

This command creates a Docker image named my-prometheus based on the Dockerfile in the current directory.

Running the Docker Container
To start the Docker container, use the following command:

sudo docker container run -i -t --rm -v /home/vagrant/opt/docker/workload/prometheus/2.46.0/conf/supervisor.ini:/etc/supervisord.conf -p 9090:9090 --entrypoint /usr/bin/supervisord my-prometheus -c /etc/supervisord.conf

Explanation
-i -t: Runs the container in interactive mode with a terminal.
--rm: Automatically removes the container when it exits.
-v /home/vagrant/opt/docker/workload/prometheus/2.46.0/conf/supervisor.ini:/etc/supervisord.conf: Mounts the supervisor.ini configuration file from your host into the container.
-p 9090:9090: Maps port 9090 on your host to port 9090 in the container.
--entrypoint /usr/bin/supervisord: Sets supervisord as the entry point for the container.
my-prometheus: Specifies the Docker image to use.
-c /etc/supervisord.conf: Uses the supervisord.conf configuration file for supervisord.
Accessing Prometheus
After starting the container, you can access the Prometheus web interface at http://localhost:9090.
